questiontext.text:
This question provides μ\mu, σ\sigma, nn, and ∑x\sum x. You are expected to determine the expected total, standard error, zz-score, and associated cumulative probability.

Population

Archie has been practicing archery for a long time, such that we can pretend her skill is constant (each arrow has the same probability distribution (see i.i.d)). Over many months, Archie has shot ten thousand arrows (their positions are shown below as dots).


From those many arrows, Archie has determined an accurate probability distribution.


Thus, Archie can determine her population mean and population standard deviation. μ=8.92\mu=8.92 σ=1.11\sigma=1.11

Sample

Today, Archie shot 45 arrows (n=45n=45). Her total score was 397 points (∑x=397\sum x = 397).


Expected total

The expected total is the product of the sample size and the population mean. expected total=nμ\text{expected total} = n\mu

“Expected total” is a bit of a misnomer. It is not necessarily likely, or even possible, for the total of a sample to equal the expected total. However, if Archie repeatedly shot 45 arrows, we expect the totals to have a mean equal to the expected total. So, maybe “average of totals” would be better terminology.

This expected total is the average of the sampling distribution implied by this question.

Calculate the expected total: {1:NUMERICAL:=401.4:2~%0%218911417:0}

(Round to the hundredths place)

Standard error

The standard error of a total is the product of the population standard deviation and the square root of the sample size. standard error of total=σn\text{standard error of total} = \sigma \sqrt{n} This standard error is the standard deviation of the sampling distribution implied by this question.

Calculate the standard error: {1:NUMERICAL:=7.4461064:2~%0%218911417:0}

(Round to the hundredths place)

Standard score

Archie would like to know how well she did today. She wants you to calculate a standard score (a zz score). To calculate the standard score of a sample total, you can use the following formula. z=∑x−nμσnz = \frac{\sum x - n\mu}{\sigma\sqrt{n}}

Calculate the standard score: {1:NUMERICAL:=-0.59:0.02~%0%218911417:0}

(Round to the hundredths place)

Cumulative probability

Archie would like to know the probability that tomorrow she shoots worse than today (if she shoots 45 arrows tomorrow). To estimate this, report the cumulative probability associated with the zz-score you calculate. This can be done with a zz table, pnorm function in R, NORM.DIST function in a spreadsheet, or with other standard normal tools.

Calculate P(Z≤z)P(Z\leq z), the cumulative probability: {1:NUMERICAL:=0.2775953:0.001~%0%218911417:0}

(Round to the ten-thousandths place)

Rating

Archie would like a rating for her day’s performance. You decide to use the following scale.

zz interval rating
−∞-\infty to -1.51 F
-1.5 to -0.51 D
-0.5 to 0.49 C
0.5 to 1.49 B
1.5 to ∞\infty A


Determine Archie’s rating: {1:MULTICHOICE:%0%A~%0%B~%0%C~%100%D~%0%F}

generalfeedback.text:
1. The expected total is nμ=401.4n\mu = 401.4
  2. The standard error is σn=7.45\sigma \sqrt{n} = 7.45
  3. Use the formula to calculate z=−0.59z=-0.59
  4. Use the zz table to find P(Z≤z)=0.2776P(Z\le z) = 0.2776
  5. The proper rating is D
